<a name = "cauchy"><b> Residue Calculus </b></a>
<p>
	<ul>
		<li> Def: Suppose the function $f(z)$ has an isolateed singularity at 
			$z = z_0.$ <em>The residue</em> of $f(z)$ at $z = z_0,$
			which we will denote as $\text{Res}(f;z_0),$ is equal to the
			coefficient of the $(z - z_0)^{-1}$ term in 
			its Laurent series expansion about that point.
			In other words,
			\[
			f(z) = \sum_{n=-\infty}^\infty a_n(z - z_0)^n \to \text{Res}(f;z_0)= a_{-1}.
			\]
		</li>
		<li> Suppose $f(z)$ has a removable singularity at $z_0,$ then
			\[
			\text{Res}(f;z_0)=0.
			\]
		</li>
		<li> Suppose $f(z)$ is holomorphic at $z_0.$ Then
			\[
			\text{Res}\left(\frac{f(z)}{z - z_0};z_0\right) = f(z_0).
			\]
		</li>
		<li> In general, suppose $f(z)$ is holomorphic at $z_0.$ Then
			\[
			\text{Res}\left(\frac{f(z)}{(z - z_0)^n};z_0\right) = \frac{1}{(n-1)!}f^{(n-1)}(z_0).
			\]
		</li>
		<li>
			Let $F(z)$ and $G(z)$ be holomorphic at $z = z_0$
			and $G(z)$ has a simple zero at $z = z_0.$ Then
			\[
			\text{Res}\left(\frac{F(z)}{G(z)};z_0\right) = \frac{F(z_0)}{G'(z_0)}.
			\]
		</li>
	</ul>
</p>

